<TITLE> Polish PM calls for law to stop German land claims </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 WARSAW, July 26 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Poland's Prime Minister Jaroslaw Kaczynski called on Thursday for changes in local law to protect Poles from property claims by Germans who lost their land when they were expelled after World War Two. The land claims have weighed on relations between Poland and Germany, which are at their worst in years since Kaczynski invoked Poland's suffering under the Nazis during negotiations about a proposed EU treaty last month. A group of more than 20 Germans expelled from Poland or their descendants filed property claims with the European Court of Human Rights and some have succeeded in Polish civil courts, mainly because of ambiguities in land records. "We will aim to bring changes in the law, which will in the end prevent these types of decisions," Kaczynski said. Speaking after a meeting with residents of the northern town of Narty, who could be facing German claims, Kaczynski criticised Polish courts for not rejecting the lawsuits. "It is clear that the courts' responsibility is to act in line with Poland's national interest," he said. Millions of Germans were expelled from their lands by the advancing Soviet army and Polish forces. Their homes and property were seized and given to Poles forced out of large chunks of eastern Poland annexed after the war by the Soviet Union. Only a handful of Polish home owners have been told to give up property so far. But the issue could become key in a possible election campaign, in which Kaczynski's Law and Justice party would battle with its junior coalition partner, the League of Polish Families, for the patriotic mantle. The leader of the far-right party, Deputy Prime Minister Roman Giertych, accused Germany earlier this month of taking advantage of its position in the European Union to undermine the post-World War Two order. He also said Germans would use a new EU treaty to win property claims in Pola
